TY  - JOUR
AU  - Berens, James L.
AU  - Cuny, Charles J.
T1  - The Capital Structure Puzzle Revisited
PY  - 1995
Y1  - 1995/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/8.4.1185
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 8
IS  - 4
SP  - 1185
EP  - 1208
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Corporate finance researchers have long been puzzled by low corporate debt ratios given debt's corporate tax advantage. This article recognizes that firm value typically reflects a growing stream of earnings, while current debt reflects a nongrowing stream of interest payments. Debt to value is therefore a distorted measure of corporate tax shielding. Even with very small debt-related costs, this may explain the observed magnitude and cross-sectional variation of debt ratios. Since this variation may be independent of tax shielding, debt ratios provide an inappropriate framework for empirically examining the trade-off theory of capital structure.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/8.4.1185
ER  - 



