TY  - JOUR
AU  - Stulz, René M.
AU  - Wasserfallen, Walter
T1  - Foreign Equity Investment Restrictions, Capital Flight, and Shareholder Wealth Maximization: Theory and Evidence
PY  - 1995
Y1  - 1995/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/8.4.1019
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 8
IS  - 4
SP  - 1019
EP  - 1057
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article provides a theory of foreign equity investment restrictions. We consider a model where the demand function for domestic shares differs between domestic and foreign investors because of deadweight costs in holding domestic and foreign securities that depend on the country of residence of investors. We show that domestic entrepreneurs maximize firm value by discriminating between domestic and foreign investors. The model implies that countries benefiting from capital flight have binding ownership restrictions such that foreign investors pay a higher price for shares than domestic investors. The empirical implications of this theory are supported by evidence from Switzerland.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/8.4.1019
ER  - 



